    <h1>Cru&#xAD;ci&#xAD;fix orchid grows best in a sunny lo&#xAD;ca&#xAD;tion and in a por&#xAD;ous grow&#xAD;ing medium</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200725/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-25"><time>2020-07-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>What is the name of this orchid (left) grow­ing in my bal­cony? Ali­son Wong</p>
    <p>This plant be­longs to the genus Epi­den­drum and is com­monly called the cru­ci­fix orchid. It is con­sid­ered an easy-to-grow orchid.</p>
    <p>It prefers a sunny lo­ca­tion and needs a well-drained and por­ous medium. Lo­cally, it is usu­ally pot­ted up in char­coal chips which per­mit fast wa­ter drainage and pro­vide am­ple aeration for the roots.</p>
    <p>•</p>
    <p>An­swers by Dr Wil­son Wong, an NParks-cer­ti­fied prac­tis­ing hor­ti­cul­tur­ist, parks man­ager and ISA-cer­ti­fied ar­borist. He is the founder of Green Cul­ture Sin­ga­pore and an ad­junct as­sis­tant pro­fes­sor (Food Sci­ence & Tech­nol­ogy) at the Na­tional Univer­sity of Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>•</p>
